# Shell scripts must stay LF regardless of the user's core.autocrlf setting.
# Bash (including Git Bash on Windows) treats \r as a literal character, so
# a CRLF shebang is not recognized and the script fails to start with
# "env: bash\r: No such file or directory". Forcing eol=lf here means
# Windows users can run scripts/*.sh without manually dos2unix-ing them
# after every fresh clone or branch switch.
*.sh text eol=lf
